Rating: 3
Very good recipe. I cut the ribs into individual pieces and placed them close to one another so I could baste the sides as well as top & bottom. I also put some salt and pepper on the ribs & used my usual method for cooking ribs in the oven: I didn't baste them until they'd been cooking about 20 min (was afraid sauce would burn). Then basted twice while cooking and one more time before putting under broiler. For all who like to try different baby back rib recipes, please try this one, from the Silver Palate cookbook, page 14: 1/2 C. Dijon mustard, 1 tsp. ground mustard, 1/2 C honey, 1/3 C. packed light brown sugar, 1/3 C. cider vinegar, 1 T. sesame oil, 1 T. soy sauce. Whisk together mustards in small saucepan. Whisk in other ingredients and heat over low heat for about 10 minutes or until flavors blend. Salt & pepper the ribs and cook in 400 degree oven for 1 hour, basting at 10 minute intervals after the ribs have cooked 30 minutes. (Before basting, reserve some of the basting sauce to serve at the table.) I give this recipe to all my friends and they get addicted quickly. Typical quote: "After my husband finished the ribs, he picked up his plate and licked it." Also, another great and quick way to cook ribs is to use the method above (i.e., don't baste until halfway through) and buy a jar of Bone Sucking Sauce (regular or hot). It is sold at Whole Foods & many farmers' markets around this area (MD). The flavor of the sauce marries perfectly with pork.

